Polynomial regression and diagnostics

2025-03-13

The Boston dataset

The ISLR2 library contains the Boston data set, which records medv (median house value) for \(506\) census tracts in Boston (Type ?Boston to find out more about the data set). More specifically, the data consist of 506 observations and 14 non constant independent variables. The variables are listed here along with their meaning:

  1. crim per capita crime rate by town.
  2. zn proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq. ft.
  3. indus proportion of non-retain business acres per town.
  4. chas - Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
  5. nox nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per million).
  6. rm average number of rooms per dwelling.
  7. age proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
  8. dis weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centers.
  9. rad index of accessibility to radial highways
  10. tax full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
  11. ptratio pupil-teacher ratio by town
  12. lstat lower status of the population (percent).
  13. medv median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

Of these, medv is the response variable while the other 12 variables are possible predictors. The goal of this analysis is to fit a regression model that best explains the variation in medv.

We first consider the single predictor lstat


1. Load the Boston data and plot lstat (x-axis) against medv (y-axis) using small green dots (that is the symbol encoded by the number 20). Then, fit a simple linear regression model, with medv as the response and lstat as the predictor, and use the function summary() to visualize the result. Finally, use the function abline() to add the regression line to the scatterplot.
library(ISLR2)
data(Boston)
plot(Boston$lstat, Boston$medv, pch=20, col="green")
lm.fit <- lm(medv ~ lstat, data=Boston)
summary(lm.fit)

2. Plot again the previous scatterplot and use the function lines() to add the regression line (note that the functions plot() and lines() need to be in the same r-chunk).

We first generate a sequence of x values.

min.lstat <- min(Boston$lstat)
max.lstat <- max(Boston$lstat)
x.seq <- seq(min.lstat, max.lstat, length=100)

Then we generate the corresponding y values, and this can be done in two different ways: 1) explicitly, that is exploiting the equation of the fitted line, as follows

beta0.hat <- coefficients(lm.fit)[1]
beta1.hat <- coefficients(lm.fit)[2]
y.seq <- beta0.hat+beta1.hat*x.seq

or, 2) using the function predict()

x.new <- data.frame(lstat = x.seq)
y.seq <- predict(lm.fit, newdata = x.new)

finally we plot both the scatterplot and the line,

plot(Boston$lstat, Boston$medv, pch=20, col="green")
lines(x.seq, y.seq, lwd=2, col="blue")

3. Obtain the vector of residuals and the vector fitted values and then use the plot the two vectors one against the other so at to produce a residual plot. Add to the plot a dotted horizontal line at x=0.
e <- residuals(lm.fit)
y.hat <- fitted.values(lm.fit)
plot(y.hat, e)
abline(h=0, lty=3)

Recall that the same result can be obtained as

plot(lm.fit, which=1, lwd=2)

7. Based on the last fitted model, produce a 95% confidence interval for the expected median value of a house for lstat=20.

We can first obtain a confidence interval for the logarithm of median value,

new.x <- data.frame(lstat=20)
log.y.hat <- predict(lm.fit.log, newdata = new.x, interval="confidence")
log.y.hat
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 2.646746 2.614639 2.678853

and then we apply the inverse transformation to obtain the required interval,

y.hat <- exp(log.y.hat)

6. Compute both the leverage statistics and the standardized residuals (this can be done with the functions hatvalues() and rstandard(), respectively). Remove the data points with either leverage value greater than 4 times the average leverege or absolute standardized residual larger than 3.5. Fit the selected model to the reduced dataset.

We first obtain the sample size and the number of paramters of the selected model.

dim(Boston)
## [1] 506  13
n <- dim(Boston)[1]
n
## [1] 506
p.plus.1 <- length(coefficients(lm.fit))
p.plus.1
## [1] 12

We then compute the threshold leverage and identify the row-indexes of the data points with leverage value above the threshold.

thr <- p.plus.1/n*4
thr
## [1] 0.09486166
lev.stat <- hatvalues(lm.fit)
i.lev <- which(lev.stat>thr)
i.lev
## 366 375 381 406 411 415 419 
## 366 375 381 406 411 415 419

Next we compute the standardized residuals and identify the row-indexes of the data points with absolute standardized residual greater than 3.5.

e.std <- rstandard(lm.fit)
i.out <- which(abs(e.std)>3.5)
i.out
## 365 369 372 373 
## 365 369 372 373

Finally, we remove the selected data points from the dataset and fit the selected model on the reduced dataset.

Boston.new <- Boston[-c(i.lev, i.out),]
